{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12475"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12475"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.78,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94014"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1075"},{"type":"tags","id":"2310"},{"type":"tags","id":"2641"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother with a one-week history of intense itching, particularly at night. He recently went camping with some friends who now have similar symptoms. The patient\u0027s younger brother, who shares a bedroom with him, has also started developing mild itching. The patient has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with erythematous inflamed papules and pustules on the flexor surfaces of the wrists, axillae, ankles, and interdigital spaces of the hands. His face and neck are spared.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrocortisone valerate 0.2% cream","Clotrimazole 1% cream","Permethrin 5% cream","Triamcinolone 0.1% ointment","Mupirocin 2% ointment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScabies is a transmissible ectoparasite infection caused by the mite \u003Cem\u003ESarcoptes scabiei. \u003C/em\u003EThis 10-year-old boy presents with intense nocturnal pruritus and characteristic lesions in a typical distribution for scabies, including the interdigital spaces, flexor wrists, axillae, and ankles, with sparing of the face. Dermatoscopy confirming the presence of burrows is diagnostic. The first-line treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Epermethrin 5% cream\u003C/strong\u003E applied to the entire body below the neck, left on for 8-14 hours (often overnight), then washed off. As scabies is highly contagious, treatment of all household contacts is also required, even if asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocortisone valerate 0.2% cream\u003C/strong\u003E is a low-potency topical corticosteroid used for inflammatory dermatoses like atopic dermatitis. While it may provide symptomatic relief of the associated pruritus, it does not treat the underlying scabies infestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly \u003Cstrong\u003Etriamcinolone 0.1% ointment\u003C/strong\u003E is a potent topical corticosteroid used for more severe inflammatory skin conditions like psoriasis, but as with hydrocortisone, it does not treat the underlying scabies infestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClotrimazole 1% cream\u003C/strong\u003E is a topical antifungal used for superficial fungal infections like tinea or candidiasis. It has no role in the treatment of scabies, which is caused by a mite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMupirocin 2% ointment\u003C/strong\u003E is a topical antibiotic used for superficial bacterial skin infections like impetigo. It is not effective against scabies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scabies is a transmissible ectoparasite infection caused by the mite Sarcoptes scabiei.","The most common sites affected by scabies include the interdigital spaces of the hands, axillae, and flexor surfaces of the wrists. The face is usually spared in adults.","Scabies is treated by the application of 5% permethrin cream to the entire body below the neck, left on for 8-14 hours, then washed off, with treatment of household contacts also required."],"references":["Nanda J, Juergens AL. Permethrin. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553150/","Gabros S, Nessel TA, Zito PM. Topical Corticosteroids. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532940/","Gilson RL, Crane JS. Scabies. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544306/","Flinders DC, De Schweinitz P. Pediculosis and scabies. Am Fam Physician. 2004 Jan 15;69(2):341-8. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2004/0115/p341.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94014"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12475"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94014"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T12:02:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T12:02:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4982"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111950"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":